Great! To update the Add Exchange Rate form with a searchable and sortable dropdown for selecting currencies (just like the one in your screenshot), you can use Angular Material's MatSelect with mat-select-search or integrate a custom dropdown like PrimeNG or ng-select with sorting and search built in.

I'll show the solution using ng-select since it supports both search and custom sorting.


---

âœ… Step-by-step Changes (Only for Add Section):

1. Install ng-select:

Run this in your Angular project:

npm install @ng-select/ng-select
``>

Import the module in your `app.module.ts` (or standalone component):
```ts
import { NgSelectModule } from '@ng-select/ng-select';

@NgModule({
  imports: [
    // other modules...
    NgSelectModule
  ]
})

2. Replace the dropdowns in Add Form HTML:

Update the From Currency and To Currency fields in the Add popup like this:

<!-- FROM CURRENCY -->
<label>From Currency</label>
<ng-select
  [items]="currencyList"
  bindLabel=""
  [(ngModel)]="newExchangeRate.fromCurr"
  [searchable]="true"
  [clearable]="true"
  placeholder="Select currency"
  [compareWith]="compareStrings"
  [sortFn]="customSortFn">
</ng-select>

<!-- TO CURRENCY -->
<label>To Currency</label>
<ng-select
  [items]="currencyList"
  bindLabel=""
  [(ngModel)]="newExchangeRate.toCurr"
  [searchable]="true"
  [clearable]="true"
  placeholder="Select currency"
  [compareWith]="compareStrings"
  [sortFn]="customSortFn">
</ng-select>

3. In your Component .ts:

Make sure you have a list of currencies populated:

currencyList: string[] = [];

ngOnInit() {
  this.fetchCurrencies();
}

fetchCurrencies() {
  this.http.get<string[]>('/api/currencies').subscribe(data => {
    this.currencyList = data;
  });
}

compareStrings(a: string, b: string): boolean {
  return a?.toLowerCase() === b?.toLowerCase();
}

customSortFn = (a: string, b: string) => a.localeCompare(b); // optional: for sorting


---

This will turn your currency inputs into searchable, sortable dropdowns (like your screenshot) without affecting the rest of the popup or the table.

Let me know if you're using a specific UI library (like PrimeNG or Material) and want this styled differently.

